description:
I am a law student at UF and have noticed several dead birds on the second floor of our library, on a ledge right outside of floor to ceiling windows. Right now I can see three clearly, and I have attached photos of them. It is difficult to take the pictures in the manner requested on the website because I cannot physically get out on the ledge, and I am taking the photos through the window.

I‚Äôm not sure how UF law would feel about this, but I really would like someone to do something about the birds because it is sad to see so many dead, even up to 5 at one time. I believe some of them piles of moss and leaves are also containing decomposing birds. As an animal lover, it is hard to study here knowing that so many have ran into the window. 

Please let me know if you have any questions and I would like to know if there is anything you guys can do at the Bird Window Collision Project.

description: Each year, the Cedar Waxwings devour every holly berry on our 15 foot tree, usually in one entire day, arriving anywhere from late February to early March (2nd photo). The downside is the death of several from window collision into our 25" cathedral ceiling windows, sadly. After finding 5 on our roof and the birds not yet done with the tree, I placed a sheet of cardboard in the window to reduce reflection and it seemed to work to prevent more deaths. Next year, once I see the birds arrive, I will try that again to see if we continue to have collisions.

tag_list: Winter, Winter 2022, 2022, Phone, UoR, Redlands, University of Redlands, Hedco Hall, by Amanda, with Amanda, dead bird, pollinator, decomposition, Scavenged, Multiple angles, broken beak, dead, native, female, Hummingbird, common
description:
A dead green colored Hummingbird that my friend Amanda found on the ground. I presume it died from a window collision, as there was no blood or obvious wounds. At the time of the observation, the eyes had already been scavenged, and the corpse smelled somewhat. I photographed as many angles as possible. 
Images 1 and 2 show that the bottom of the beak was broken. Image 5 shows the throat. Image 6 shows the bird from a top down angle while image 7 shows its tail from below. Images 8 and 9 show the small wing. Image 10 shows the missing eyes and a closeup of the feathers of the face. Image 12-16 show closeup views of one of its feet. Image 17 shows the neck feathers when the head is tipped back. I compressed the neck feathers to show how much of the Hummingbird's size is plumage, which can be seen in image 18 and 19. Image 20 shows a size comparison relative to my hand.

Amanda also posted this hummingbird, which can be seen here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/105758903

Update: as of 4 days later, the corpse is no longer where I left it, scavenged I presume.

Hopefully this variety of angles can be useful as an ID resource :)

description:
Found about a foot or two away from the outside of the south side garden fence. We have not had any noticeable signs of window collisions with the house since installing shades, BUT the north side of the house (facing the garden, but not particularly close to it) does not have shades in all of its windows. I will talk to the property owner about decals and see if it results in fewer dead songbirds near the garden and coop. If not, I have no idea what‚Äôs killing them; I find dead birds in that area, and ONLY that area, every couple of months. None of the hens have died or shown signs of illness; and with the exception of 2+ towhees, none of the dead birds have been of species that frequent the garden. I‚Äôve tried finding information on whether birds often die from fence collisions, but all I‚Äôve found are reports on barbed wire and electric fences, neither of which apply in this instance. The only time I‚Äôve seen one of the deceased birds *before* it died was a Chipping Sparrow that showed signs of possible neurological distress/damage. I was going to call the local rehabber in the morning, but the bird did not survive the night. I have not observed any other wild birds acting similarly discombobulated since then, only the corpses. We do not have any cats, and our dogs only go outside under supervision, so I do not think predation is a likely cause. While a flock of chickens is certainly capable of killing a wild bird, I would expect to find the bodies of slower species like quail and doves (both of which visit the garden regularly) before thrushes and sparrows, if this were the case.

Well, all this to say: I haven‚Äôt documented every dead bird I‚Äôve found around there, but I guess I‚Äôll start doing so now, and maybe suss out what‚Äôs killing our songbirds.
place_guess: Washington County, US-OR, US

description: I came home from a walk in the park to find this innocent creature had been killed too soon by a window collision. I will not pretend that I am competent enough to write a proper obituary for such a beautiful animal. All I can say is that I hope she now flies forever in an infinite blue expanse. Hundreds of millions of birds are killed in window collisions each year in the United States alone; please, if you are able to, consider treating your windows with marking techniques such as tempera paint, soap, decals, dot patterns or tape, screens, netting, or Acopian BirdSavers to make windows more visible for birds and reduce risk of a collision. If possible, turn off nonessential lights at night in your home or business, especially during migration periods (March 1-June 15 and August 15-November 30 in Texas). My family is planning to take steps to make our home safer for local wildlife. We buried this Cedar Waxwing‚ÄîI hope we never have to bury another one.

description:
Images provided by Soren Goldsmith  https://sorengoldsmith.com/ 
First hand account from Soren: "The original sighting was posted at 2:38 pm on February 2nd, however it's safe to assume it was found a bit before that. I attached the photo that was posted on snapchat to this email as well. It appears to be alive in that photo. The photo shows the owl almost in the direct center of the courtyard.

I arrived at 3:35 pm. At that point the owl was clearly dead. I was one of two people there. The bird had been moved at some point but I'm not sure when or by who. 

I'd like to note that it's not a confirmed window collision, however that seems the most likely. The owl had been living in a tree about 10 feet away within the Adams courtyard for months prior to this. There was visible whitewash on the pavement below its roost. "
